=====Idioms=====
{{col-top|2|id}}
* {{ja-r|糞にする|くそ に する}}: “to turn something into shit; to treat something as shit” → to make something worthless; to treat something as worthless
* {{ja-r|糞の役にも立たぬ|くそ の やく に も たたぬ}}: “not even standing in the role of shit” → not even good for shit
*: (See {{ja-r|役に立つ|やく に たつ}}: “to be useful, to play a role”)
* {{ja-r|糞も味噌も一緒|くそ も みそ も いっしょ}}: “both crap and miso together” → a situation where it is difficult to tell the good from the bad
{{col-bottom}}

====Interjection====
{{ja-pos|interjection|くそ}}

# {{lb|ja|often|vulgar}} [[shit]], [[crap]]
#: {{ja-x|'''クソ！''' [[玄%関]]の[[鍵]]を[[かける|かけ]][[忘れる|忘れ]]た！|'''クソ！''' げん%かん の かぎ を かけ-わすれた！|'''Shit!''' I forgot to lock the front door!}}

=====Usage notes=====
* This is not considered as profane as the English glosses. For instance, a child of five using the Japanese interjection ''kuso'' would be unremarkable, whereas it would be very socially inappropriate for a child of five to use the English interjection {{m|en|shit}}.

====Prefix====
